# gRPC C++ Channel Creation and Stub Instantiation API

## Overview

A **channel** is the fundamental connectivity abstraction in gRPC C++. It models
a long-lived connection to a single endpoint (or a name-resolved set of
endpoints) and is the object from which all stubs and RPCs are created.

The typical lifecycle is:

```
CreateChannel / CreateCustomChannel
        │
        ▼
std::shared_ptr<grpc::Channel>
        │
        ▼
ServiceName::NewStub(channel)
        │
        ▼
std::unique_ptr<ServiceName::Stub>   ──►  RPC calls
```

Channels are thread-safe and are designed to be shared across threads and
across multiple stubs. Creating a channel is relatively expensive; prefer
creating one channel per target endpoint and reusing it for the lifetime of
the application.

**Required headers:**

```cpp
#include <grpcpp/grpcpp.h>          // umbrella header (recommended)

// Or include individually:
#include <grpcpp/create_channel.h>
#include <grpcpp/security/credentials.h>
#include <grpcpp/support/channel_arguments.h>
```

---

## Channel Creation Functions

### `grpc::CreateChannel`

```cpp
// Declared in: include/grpcpp/create_channel.h
namespace grpc {

std::shared_ptr<Channel> CreateChannel(
    const grpc::string& target,
    const std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials>& creds);

}  // namespace grpc
```

Creates a channel to `target` using the supplied credentials and default
channel arguments.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `target` | `const grpc::string&` | URI of the endpoint to connect to. Accepts `host:port`, `dns:///host:port`, `ipv4:addr:port`, `ipv6:[addr]:port`, and other name-resolver schemes. |
| `creds` | `std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials>` | Credentials that authenticate the channel. If the pointer is null or invalid, a **lame channel** is returned on which every RPC fails immediately. |

**Return value:** `std::shared_ptr<grpc::Channel>` — never null, but may be a
lame channel when credentials are invalid.

**Example — insecure channel:**

```cpp
#include <grpcpp/grpcpp.h>
#include "helloworld.grpc.pb.h"

auto channel = grpc::CreateChannel(
    "localhost:50051",
    grpc::InsecureChannelCredentials());

auto stub = helloworld::Greeter::NewStub(channel);
```

---

### `grpc::CreateCustomChannel`

```cpp
// Declared in: include/grpcpp/create_channel.h
namespace grpc {

std::shared_ptr<Channel> CreateCustomChannel(
    const grpc::string& target,
    const std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials>& creds,
    const ChannelArguments& args);

}  // namespace grpc
```

> **Warning:** For advanced use and testing **only**. Override default channel
> arguments only when necessary. Prefer `CreateChannel` for production code
> unless a specific tuning argument is required.

Creates a channel to `target` with explicit control over channel arguments.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `target` | `const grpc::string&` | URI of the endpoint to connect to (same schemes as `CreateChannel`). |
| `creds` | `std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials>` | Credentials for the channel. A null or invalid pointer yields a lame channel. |
| `args` | `const ChannelArguments&` | Fine-grained channel options (message sizes, keepalive, load-balancing policy, etc.). See [ChannelArguments](#channelarguments) below. |

**Return value:** `std::shared_ptr<grpc::Channel>` — never null, but may be a
lame channel when credentials are invalid.

**Example — custom channel with message-size and keepalive tuning:**

```cpp
#include <grpcpp/grpcpp.h>
#include "helloworld.grpc.pb.h"

grpc::ChannelArguments args;
args.SetMaxReceiveMessageSize(16 * 1024 * 1024);  // 16 MiB
args.SetMaxSendMessageSize(16 * 1024 * 1024);     // 16 MiB
args.SetInt(GRPC_ARG_KEEPALIVE_TIME_MS, 30000);   // ping every 30 s
args.SetInt(GRPC_ARG_KEEPALIVE_TIMEOUT_MS, 10000);

auto channel = grpc::CreateCustomChannel(
    "backend.example.com:443",
    grpc::SslCredentials(grpc::SslCredentialsOptions()),
    args);

auto stub = helloworld::Greeter::NewStub(channel);
```

---

### `grpc::experimental::CreateCustomChannelWithInterceptors`

```cpp
// Declared in: include/grpcpp/create_channel.h
namespace grpc::experimental {

std::shared_ptr<Channel> CreateCustomChannelWithInterceptors(
    const grpc::string& target,
    const std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials>& creds,
    const ChannelArguments& args,
    std::vector<
        std::unique_ptr<experimental::ClientInterceptorFactoryInterface>>
        interceptor_creators);

}  // namespace grpc::experimental
```

> **Warning:** Experimental API — subject to change without notice.

Extends `CreateCustomChannel` with a list of client-side interceptor factories
that are invoked for every RPC on the channel.

| Parameter | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `target` | `const grpc::string&` | URI of the endpoint. |
| `creds` | `std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials>` | Channel credentials. |
| `args` | `const ChannelArguments&` | Channel arguments. |
| `interceptor_creators` | `std::vector<std::unique_ptr<ClientInterceptorFactoryInterface>>` | Ordered list of interceptor factories. Interceptors run in vector order on the way out and in reverse order on the way back. |

---

## `grpc::ChannelCredentials` Hierarchy

`ChannelCredentials` is an opaque base class. Instances are always held via
`std::shared_ptr` and are created through the factory functions described
below. The class itself has no public constructors.

```
grpc::ChannelCredentials          (abstract base)
├── InsecureChannelCredentials()  — no TLS, no auth
├── SslCredentials()              — TLS with optional mTLS
├── GoogleDefaultCredentials()    — ADC for Google services
├── experimental::AltsCredentials()   — ALTS (GCP only)
├── experimental::LocalCredentials()  — UDS / local loopback
├── experimental::TlsCredentials()    — advanced TLS (gRFC A29)
└── CompositeChannelCredentials() — channel creds + call creds
```

`grpc::CallCredentials` attaches per-call authentication tokens and can be
layered on top of any `ChannelCredentials` via `CompositeChannelCredentials`.

---

### Insecure Credentials

```cpp
std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials> grpc::InsecureChannelCredentials();
```

Returns credentials for an **unencrypted, unauthenticated** channel. Use only
in development, testing, or trusted private networks.

**Example:**

```cpp
auto channel = grpc::CreateChannel(
    "localhost:50051",
    grpc::InsecureChannelCredentials());
```

---

### SSL / TLS Credentials

```cpp
// Declared in: include/grpcpp/security/credentials.h

struct grpc::SslCredentialsOptions {
    grpc::string pem_root_certs;   // PEM-encoded CA root certificates.
                                   // Empty → use system/environment defaults.
    grpc::string pem_private_key;  // PEM-encoded client private key (mTLS).
                                   // Empty → no client certificate.
    grpc::string pem_cert_chain;   // PEM-encoded client certificate chain (mTLS).
                                   // Empty → no client certificate.
};

std::shared_ptr<ChannelCredentials> grpc::SslCredentials(
    const SslCredentialsOptions& options);
```

Builds standard TLS credentials. When `pem_root_certs` is empty, gRPC uses
the system default CA bundle or the path in the
`GRPC_DEFAULT_SSL_ROOTS_FILE_PATH` environment variable.

Providing `pem_private_key` and `pem_cert_chain` enables **mutual TLS (mTLS)**,
where the client authenticates itself to the server.

**Example — server-side TLS only (most common):**

```cpp
grpc::SslCredentialsOptions ssl_opts;
// pem_root_certs left empty → use system roots
auto channel = grpc::CreateChannel(
    "api.example.com:443",
    grpc::SslCredentials(ssl_opts));
```

**Example — mutual TLS (mTLS):**

```cpp
grpc::SslCredentialsOptions ssl_opts;
ssl_opts.pem_root_certs  = ReadFile("ca.pem");
ssl_opts.pem_private_key = ReadFile("client.key");
ssl_opts.pem_cert_chain  = ReadFile("client.crt");

auto channel = grpc::CreateChannel(
    "api.example.com:443",
    grpc::SslCredentials(ssl_opts));
```

**Example — override SSL target name (testing only):**

```cpp
grpc::SslCredentialsOptions ssl_opts;
ssl_opts.pem_root_certs = ReadFile("test-ca.pem");

grpc::ChannelArguments args;
args.SetSslTargetNameOverride("test-server");  // matches CN/SAN in test cert

auto channel = grpc::CreateCustomChannel(
    "localhost:50051",
    grpc::SslCredentials(ssl_opts),
    args);
```

